# LifeOS — Project Rules for Cursor

The authoritative rules for this project live in [CLAUDE.md](mdc:CLAUDE.md) at the repo root. Read it before generating, editing, or reviewing code. The summary below is a pointer, not a replacement.

## Critical rules (do not violate)

### 1. No real user data in any committed file
Never include real names, company names, school names, activities, dates, email addresses, or task descriptions from the user's life in any file that is committed. Applies universally: source, prompts, docs, feature specs, review docs, test fixtures, comments. Use placeholders like `[USER]`, `Task A`, `Project X`, `Child A`, `Example Corp`. Full list of forbidden/allowed examples is in [CLAUDE.md](mdc:CLAUDE.md).

### 2. One-time scripts stay in `scripts/scratch/`
Data fixes, debug dumps, and migration patches go in `scripts/scratch/` (gitignored) and are never committed. They are the #1 source of personal-data leaks. Only permanent infrastructure scripts belong in `scripts/`.

### 3. Architecture boundaries are sacred
- TypeScript owns: routing, state, file I/O, conflict detection, writes, summarizing, token budgets.
- LLM owns: language understanding, judgment, suggestions, natural-language reply.
- One LLM call per user phrase. No multi-agent pipelines.
- LLM always returns JSON via tool use (`submit_action_plan`); TypeScript executes the plan.
- Per-intent context only — do not send all files to all intents. Every intent has a token budget.
- File writes go through `filesystem.ts` (temp-file-then-rename).
- Use `state.userProfile.timezone` for date operations, not system locale.

### 4. App runs continuously
The app is opened once and stays running for days. Never design features that only trigger on app load, startup, or mount. Every periodic check uses `setInterval` and respects `loadingRef` / `inboxProcessingRef` guards.

## Required updates when changing code

When adding functionality, changing architecture, or adding data files / intents / modules, update:
- `docs/new_architecture_typescript.md` — single source of truth for architecture.
- `README.md` — features, scripts, data files, modules, project tree.
- `packages/feature-kit/features/` — feature backlog via the feature-kit CLI (provide category, moscow, priority, release, tags; move status through the pipeline: Planned → Design Reviewed → In Progress → Code Reviewed → Testing → Done).

## Output style

- User-facing messages: plain, non-technical language. No file names, JSON keys, or system jargon.
- Focus on outcomes ("Your plan is ready"), not actions ("Wrote focus_brief.json").
- Chat reply for planning intents: 1–2 sentences max; details go in the Focus Brief.

## Learned patterns (from prior reviews)

- Haiku→Sonnet fallback is gated by `SONNET_FALLBACK_INTENTS`. Simple CRUD intents fail gracefully, don't escalate.
- Injected LLM functions (`injectRefreshLlm`) bypass the `llm.ts` circuit breaker — callers must check `isCircuitOpen()` first.
- When wiring a module into the UI, check whether the headless runner also needs it. It is the biggest cost center.
- One Sonnet call per day (morning plan). Evening + light checks use Tier 2 Haiku refresh. Weekly plan is the only other Sonnet call.
- `lifeos.db` lives on a local path (`DB_PATH`), not on Google Drive. Hourly backup copies it to the cloud folder.
- When adding fields to `Task`, update: `types/index.ts`, `db/queries/tasks.ts` (rowToTask + insertTask + updateTask), `executor.ts` (defaults), `recurringProcessor.ts`, and test fixtures.
